BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/HP-Slider-Images-Mobile-1.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260604T073620Z
DESCRIPTION:What does vulnerability look like? What does care feel like?\nThese are the questions that artist afra eisma leaves us with in warrior garments.\n\nJoin us for the final session of reflective feminist reading sessions\, developed in collaboration with Zubaan and facilitated by Laxmi Murthy. Together\, we will explore gender-based violence—its lived realities\, and the possibilities of resistance\, solidarity\, and healing. Through stories\, essays\, and personal reflections\, you are invited to engage with the exhibition at your own pace\, in a space that encourages listening\, sharing\, and care.\n\nNote: This is the final session in a series presented alongside Warrior Garments. Reading materials for each will be shared after registration.\n\nTrigger Warning: The sessions may include discussions on sexual violence.
DTEND:20260621T073000Z
DTSTART:20260621T053000Z
SUMMARY:Holding Space: Feminist Reading Circle
UID:1302@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/holding-space-feminist-reading-circle-3/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Untitled-design-10.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260603T105119Z
DESCRIPTION:Magnolia campbellii H.f. &amp\; T\; Illustrations of Himalayan Plants\; Author &amp\; Artist: Joseph Dalton Hooker\; Lithographer: Walter Hood Fitch\; 1855\; Image courtesy of the Missouri Botanical Garden Library via the Biodiversity Heritage Library\nIn this walk\, Abhishek Khan traces the backstory of the few surviving—and many lost—flowers and plants that were painted in Lalbagh. As we observe the fragrant flowers and leaves around us\, we learn how today's botanical collection are a product of the aesthetics established by colonial empire\, continuing to influence what we see in gardens today. \n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260614T040000Z
DTSTART:20260614T023000Z
SUMMARY:A Fragrance Walk at Lalbagh Botanical Garden
UID:1297@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/a-fragrance-walk-at-lalbagh-botanical-garden/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/image.jpeg
CATEGORIES:Performances,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260522T114141Z
DESCRIPTION:Blending storytelling\, drag performance\, dance\, and multimedia elements\, the program traces KaMani Sutra’s journey of discovering femininity while navigating life as an adult immigrant in the United States.\n\nRooted in the richness of Indian drag aesthetics and cultural influences\, this artist's showcase reflects on identity\, migration\, and self-expression\, contrasting the freedom of living authentically in a foreign land with the complexities of belonging and visibility. Through short performances\, video\, and consensual audience participation\, the lecture-performance-artist showcase challenges ideas around the model minority myth\, binary gender\, and colonial saviorship.\n\nAt once celebratory and reflective\, the program honours intergenerational queerness\, LGBTQ+ community\, saris\, mujras\, divine femininity\, and the transformative power of self-love.\n\nThis programme is part of LGBTQIA+ programming and is an attempt to amplify narratives from within the queer community through film\, dialogue\, and collective reflection.
DTEND:20260607T140000Z
DTSTART:20260607T123000Z
SUMMARY:Being Queen is My Resistance: Lessons in Drag Mythology and Migration
UID:1294@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/being-queen-is-my-resistance-lessons-in-drag-mythology-and-migration/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Abhishek-Khan-is-a-research-based-artist-designer-and-storyteller-who-works-under-the-pen-name-Hand-Jobs-Inc.-His-practice-explores-the-relationships-between-people-memory-and-the-natural-worl-1.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260603T121914Z
DESCRIPTION:Untitled\, Durgaprasad Bandi\,2022\, Cyanotype\, MAC.02155\nThis workshop introduces participants to cyanotype process through direct engagement with materials\, light\, and composition. Rooted in the legacy of early photographic image-making\, the session moves from technical understanding to exploratory making.\n\nBeginning with an introduction to the history and context of cyanotype\, participants then prepare coated surfaces\, compose images using botanical specimens\, and expose prints using sunlight and UV sources. \n\nOn experimentation with form\, layering\, and variations in exposure and washing\, participants understand how the process responds to material and environmental conditions. \n\nThis programme is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260613T090000Z
DTSTART:20260613T060000Z
SUMMARY:Prints in Blue
UID:1299@map-india.org
